\section{Survey collections}{

When applied to a \code{survey_collection}, \code{pull()} extracts the column from
each member and combines the per-member vectors via \code{\link[vctrs:vec_c]{vctrs::vec_c()}}.
Detection of missing columns uses class-catch only — both \code{var} and \code{name}
flow through a single \code{tryCatch} handler that re-raises
\code{vctrs_error_subscript_oob} / \code{rlang_error_data_pronoun_not_found} as
\code{surveytidy_error_collection_verb_failed}.

Naming options:
\itemize{
\item \code{name = NULL} (default) — unnamed combined vector.
\item \code{name = coll@id} — by-survey naming sentinel: each combined element
is named by its source survey. The sentinel string is whatever
\code{coll@id} resolves to (default \code{.survey}; user-set values like \code{"wave"}
work identically).
\item \code{name = "<other_column>"} — passes through to \code{dplyr::pull}'s
\code{name} arg unchanged (per-row names from another column inside each
member), then combined across surveys via the same \code{\link[vctrs:vec_c]{vctrs::vec_c()}}
path as the values.
}

If \code{\link[vctrs:vec_c]{vctrs::vec_c()}} raises \code{vctrs_error_incompatible_type} (e.g., one
member has the column as numeric and another as character), the error is
re-raised as \code{surveytidy_error_collection_pull_incompatible_types} with
\code{parent = cnd} and the column name and conflicting surveys. No
auto-coercion — \code{pull} returns a single vector and silent coercion would
mask the kind of data-type bug users almost certainly want surfaced.
(\code{glimpse.survey_collection} auto-coerces with a footer; the divergence is
intentional — \code{glimpse} is diagnostic, \code{pull} is computational.)
